m":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Glynn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Malachy, Dermot, Eamon, Liam, Niall, Ronan, Sean Patrick, Siobhan.","Welsh and Cornish: topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, Welsh <i>glyn</i>, Cornish <i>glin</i>, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Glynn (Cornwall).","Irish (Galway): shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mag Fhloinn</b> (see   McGlynn  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Glines","meanings":["Welsh: possibly an altered form of   Glynn  , with English excrescent -s."]},{"name":"McGlynn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Bridie, Colm, Declan, Donovan, Sean Patrick, Thomas Patrick.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Fhloinn</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Flann</i> ‘red, crimson’."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh Glynn was born in 1420, in Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, his father, Jenkin Glynn, was 25 and his mother, Jane verch Evan ap Meredith, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Joan Cotton. He died in 1509, in his hometown, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1420–1509":"1420–1509","1425–1471":"1425–1471","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1442–1530":"1442–1530","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1395–1421":"1395–1421","17 May 1421":"17. mai 1421","1425":"1425","1456":"1456","1412":"1412","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1530":"1530","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","1509":"1509","23 April 1456":"23. aprill 1456","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales","London, England":"London, England","England, United Kingdom":"England"},"fi":{"1420–1509":"1420–1509","1425–1471":"1425–1471","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1442–1530":"1442–1530","1395–Male":"1395–Kuollut","1395–1421":"1395–1421","17 May 1421":"17. toukokuuta 1421","1425":"1425","1456":"1456","1412":"1412","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1530":"1530","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","1509":"1509","23 April 1456":"23. huhtikuuta 1456","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales","London, England":"London, England","England, United Kingdom":"England"},"fr":{"1420–1509":"1420–1509","1425–1471":"1425–1471","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1442–1530":"1442–1530","1395–Male":"1395–Décédé","1395–1421":"1395–1421","17 May 1421":"17 mai 1421","1425":"1425","1456":"1456","1412":"1412","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1530":"1530","1395":"1395","1471":"1471","1509":"1509","23 April 1456":"23 avril 1456","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Galles","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Hugh Glynn est né en 1420, à Mo